# Suno Premiere Pro Plugin
AI-powered music generation plugin for Adobe Premiere Pro with web app backend integration.

## Current Focus
Section: Architecture Research & Planning
Files: This session was research-only; no implementation files created yet

## Last Session (2025-12-16)
- Completed comprehensive architecture research using 7 build-research agents
- Researched GitHub patterns for CEP plugins, Suno API integration, audio analysis
- Documented full system architecture across 7 domains:
  - Premiere Pro CEP Plugin Architecture (Bolt CEP, CSInterface, ExtendScript)
  - Suno API Integration (unofficial middleware, cookie auth, polling)
  - Web Backend (NestJS + BullMQ + PostgreSQL + R2)
  - Audio Analysis Pipeline (librosa, key/genre/mood detection, prompt generation)
  - Authentication & Sync (OAuth 2.0 Device Flow, JWT, chunked downloads)
  - Frontend UI (Next.js + shadcn/ui + TanStack Query + wavesurfer.js)
  - Testing & DevOps (Vitest, Playwright, pytest, Docker Compose, GitHub Actions)
- Stopped at: Research complete, ready for implementation decisions

## Architecture Decisions
- **Plugin**: CEP with Bolt CEP build tool (note: CEP deprecated Sept 2026, consider UXP)
- **Backend**: NestJS preferred over FastAPI for native BullMQ integration
- **Storage**: Cloudflare R2 (zero egress fees for audio streaming)
- **Real-time**: SSE over WebSocket (simpler, CEP-compatible)
- **Auth**: OAuth 2.0 Device Flow for plugin, standard OAuth for web

## Next Steps
1. Decide on CEP vs UXP for plugin approach
2. Set up monorepo structure (pnpm workspaces or turborepo)
3. Implement backend API skeleton with NestJS + BullMQ
4. Create audio analysis pipeline with librosa
5. Build CEP panel UI with Bolt CEP

## Key Technical Notes
- Suno has no official API - requires middleware proxy (gcui-art/suno-api pattern)
- Suno generation takes 30-120s - use polling with exponential backoff
- CEP panels use Chrome DevTools debugging on localhost:8088
- Redis requires `maxmemory-policy noeviction` for BullMQ
